div.p:
While we can only infer Margaretʼs objections based on the content of the original verse and on Ruskinʼs substitution, 
                                the topics that drew her censorship seem evident enough. The constellation Medusaʼs Head must have seemed too horrible, 
                                so it was replaced by the modern wonder of the Telescope, a constellation that also advantageously sponsored patriotism for its assocation 
                                with the British astronomer William Herschel (1738–1822). Even the “furious lynx” needed to be tamed to become only “keen‐eyed”. 
                                The religious associations with the constellation, the Altar, were dangerously pagan, so the epithet “gods fire” was added 
                                to lend a Biblical context. One change was demanded apparently to prevent a jest from disturbing the gravity of the subject; 
                                and some lines seem to have been assigned an × for no discernible reason other than poetic: the trite and redundant epithet “pretty” was rejected, 
                                and an imperfect rhyme needed mending 
                                (see textual and contextual glosses hanging from line 14, “Then the dread medusas head”; 
                                line 30, “After that the furious lynx”; 
                                line 44, “Next to it the altar”; 
                                lines 17 and 64, “After that doth come the lyre” and “I wish I had not observed the lyre”; 
                                lines 12 and 40, “Then the very pretty swan” and “Next the very pretty crane”; 
                                lines 41 and 42, “Antinous and arrow soon” and “After it the southern crown”).
